# Item Art Generation

When asked to create or update item images for this project, follow these rules to keep the art consistent.

## Visual Style

- **Overall look**
  - Make a single, isolated game item centered in frame.
  - No background, no props, no text, no logo.
  - Transparent background PNG (no visible background color or gradient).
- **Rendering style**
  - 2D stylized, cartoony illustration.
  - Clean, thick dark outline around the item.
  - Simple, readable shapes with slightly exaggerated proportions.
  - Soft cell shading with 2–3 tone highlights and shadows (similar to a mobile RPG inventory icon).
- **Lighting and color**
  - Single soft light source from the upper left.
  - Subtle glossy highlights on shiny/metal/magic surfaces.
  - High contrast, saturated colors so the item reads clearly at small sizes.

## Composition & Framing

- Item must be fully visible with no cropping.
- Item must face the viewer in a clear, readable angle (3/4 or straight-on, whichever is most iconic).
- Center the item and keep margins roughly equal on all sides.
- Avoid extreme perspective or complex scenes.

## Technical Constraints

- Generate square images with a size of 384x384
- Keep the file size of the image small
- Output format should be PNG with transparency.
- Keep edges clean so the icon looks good on dark and light UI backgrounds.

## Prompt Template

When generating a new item image, use a prompt like this and replace the placeholders:

```text
Highly detailed 2D game inventory icon of a single [ITEM NAME] for a fantasy crafting RPG, in the style of a cartoony mobile game.

The [ITEM NAME] should represent: [ESSENCES / THEMES, e.g. wealth, technology, magic, life, dark, earth, light].

Visual style: bold dark outline, simple stylized shapes, saturated colors, 2–3 tone cell shading, soft light from the upper left, subtle glossy highlights where appropriate. No text, no logo, no extra props.

Framing: item centered, fully visible, on a transparent background, square canvas, no background elements, just the object.
```

## Mapping From Code to Art

When `BaseItem` is mentioned, use the following as guidance:

- `apple`: bright red apple similar to existing icon.
- `rock`: small, chunky gray stone with simple facets.
- `gear`: metal gear / cog with a slight metallic shine.
- `potionFlask` → “glass potion flask” (empty by default unless specified).
- `copperFlorin` → “copper coin” icon.
- `silverFlorin` → “silver coin” icon.
- `goldFlorin` → “gold coin” icon.
- `lens`: circular glass lens with light/technology hints.
- `humanSkull`: stylized human skull icon with mild dark tone (but still cartoony, not gory).

When creating new items, derive their look from:

- Their `name` and any mention of essences (e.g. wealth, technology, magic, life, dark, earth, light).
- Their rarity/quality (junk, common, good) if provided: higher quality can have slightly more ornamentation and subtle glow.

Create an Xcode .imageset under Items/Resource/Assets.xcassets 
Once an image is generated, run `swiftgen`.